{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475295"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:31:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:31:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.05,0.69,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54057"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5082"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39530"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3730"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"9278"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8619"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9202"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16285"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54057"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a six-month history of fever, fatigue, shortness of breath, and intermittent bleeding from the nose and gums. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. He looks pale, and pinpoint haemorrhages are visible on both lower limbs. Abdominal examination reveals a palpable liver and spleen. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin 50 g/L (115-155)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count 2 x 10^9/L (5-15)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelets 25 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPeripheral blood smear shows blast cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute myeloid leukaemia","Chronic myeloid leukaemia","Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia","Chronic lymphocytic leukaemia","Non-Hodgkin lymphoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute lymphoblastic leukaemia (ALL)\u003C/strong\u003E. The key findings include pancytopaenia (decreased levels of all three cell lines), resulting in anaemia (fatigue, pallor, shortness of breath), fever likely due to leukopaenia, and petechiae and bleeding as a result of thrombocytopenia. The presence of hepatosplenomegaly is also characteristic of ALL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALL is the most common paediatric cancer. It is a malignancy of lymphoid cells affecting B and T cell lineages, promoting uncontrolled proliferation of immature blast cells that replace the normal haematopoietic cells of the marrow, resulting in marrow failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute myeloid leukaemia (AML)\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in the adult population. While signs and symptoms are usually similar to ALL, diagnosis is typically made on bone marrow biopsy, which shows Auer rods - a feature absent in ALL.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic myeloid leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in the 4th to 6th decade of life and rarely presents in childhood. It is characterised by uncontrolled proliferation of myeloid cells. Laboratory investigations typically show anaemia, a very high white cell count (\u003E100,000), and variable platelet count. Massive splenomegaly is an important feature of CML.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic lymphocytic leukaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most common leukaemias in adults but rarely presents in children. It is often asymptomatic and an incidental finding on full blood count. When symptomatic, it is characterised by weight loss, sweats, enlarged rubbery non-tender lymph nodes, splenomegaly, and hepatomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-Hodgkin lymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a malignancy of lymphoid tissues mainly affecting lymph nodes. It is more common in older males with a weakened immune system. It usually presents with lymphadenopathy. In some cases, it can present with extra-nodal involvement such as gut (MALT), skin (mycosis fungoides), oropharynx, bone, lung, or CNS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe definitive diagnosis of ALL is made by bone marrow biopsy, showing \u003E20% blast cells. Treatment typically involves a combination of chemotherapy, targeted therapy, and in some cases, stem cell transplantation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia (ALL) is the most common cancer in children, presenting with features of bone marrow failure (pancytopaenia) and infiltration (hepatosplenomegaly).","Definitive diagnosis of ALL is by bone marrow biopsy showing \u003E20% blast cells."],"references":["Puckett Y, Chan O. Acute Lymphocytic Leukemia. [Updated 2022 Jun 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459149/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39530"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39530"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-29T11:14:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-29T11:14:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5082"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54057"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relat